At the moment, the government’s public standing is severely battered, with doubts frequently voiced about whether anyone “in there” has anything figured out. Depending on who you speak to, two dire scenarios are suggested: impending government failure, or wholesale state failure.
Paradoxically, we live at a time of tremendous burgeoning of ministerial clout. Today’s Cabinet secretaries are arguably the most explicitly empowered cohort in Kenya’s Executive history.





The President has formally delegated important functions to Cabinet secretaries, to be performed individually through line mandates, or through thematic Cabinet sub-committees and multiagency focal points.
Essentially, they have the ability to speak and act on behalf of government in meaningful ways. Obviously, the intention of this empowerment was to hasten the President’s feet and hands in delivering his agenda and burnishing a legacy of transformational achievement.
A lavish incentive comes with this: our Cabinet secretaries are formidably installed in the heart of Kenya’s official VIP culture as veritable demigods; they lack for nothing.
Yet here we are. How come, and what gives, then? This newspaper recently reported that the president’s wishes have been falling on deaf ears since 2015 in regards to e-procurement (All bark and no bite: A look at Uhuru’s often ignored e-tendering orders, September 7, 2020).



