Casual treatment
With rampant irregularities dogging the entire public sector, the casual treatment of the presidential directive by his subordinates is cause for a lot of angst. I may add at this point that this defiance of the President is not necessarily confined to procurement matters, and may be key to understanding a lot of the things going south in our country today.
The Public Service Commission’s annual evaluation reports on compliance with the National Values and Principles of Governance and the Values and Principles of the Public Service illuminates the extent of this bureaucratic insolence.
Consider, first, that these evaluations are the basis of the President’s mandatory report under Article 232 as well as the State of the Nation Address. Consider also that when the commission tracked compliance with presidential directives, it measured a considerable failure rate. Further, ponder the fact that the commission has had to sternly remark about ministries, departments and agencies wilfully refusing to participate in the evaluation.
Finally, please reflect on the fact that no Cabinet secretary is on record taking issue with this recalcitrance, nor expressing any remorse for such sabotage of the president’s constitutional mandate. What is the source of this impunity?



