It seems that many functionaries misconstrued the delegation of functions and forgot their place. Instead, they imagine themselves as being in a political settlement with the Chief, like the barons-warlords of the Magna Carta. As a result, the relationship between principal and agent implicit in such situations has all but collapsed, or been reversed!
A principal delegates a task to an agent, who is contracted to act at all times in the principal’s best interests. The agent is fully empowered to the extent necessary to secure the principal’s interests.
Monitoring mechanism
But the whole point of the relationship is to free the principal to do other things, and basically trust the agent. Without effective monitoring, nothing stops the agent from selfishly (ab)using their informational advantage and presence on the ground, and the principal will be none the wiser.
Our parliament long ago abdicated their role of becoming this effective monitoring mechanism. This abdication occurred simultaneously with the tremendous increase in Executive muscularity, which was then donated in good faith to secretaries.
Although the most muscular of these secretaries never miss a chance to proclaim to the world that they are helping the President achieve this and that, our dismal situation as a country testifies to the contrary. Without a doubt, they are helping themselves.



